In [78]:
G = nx.Graph()
color_map=[]
# This helps insure that no edge is left out
for n in range(0, len(politics_edges)): 
    G.add_edges_from(
        [(politics_edges['Source'][n], politics_edges['Target'][n])])
#This colors the nodes in the node table accordingly
for n in G:
    if politics_nodes['political_ideology'][n] == 'neutral':
        color_map.append('gray')
    elif politics_nodes['political_ideology'][n] == 'conservative':
        color_map.append('red')
    else:
        color_map.append('blue')
# This helps relabel the nodes as the Labels from the nodes table
G = nx.relabel_nodes(G, politics_nodes['Label'])
#This helps the viewer read the graph more easily
plt.figure(figsize=(25,25))
nx.draw(G, node_color=color_map, with_labels=True)
plt.show()

Note: Red=Conservative, Gray=Neutral, Blue=Liberal

3.¶

My network has 105 nodes and 441 edges. It is not directed, but it is connected. The network also has conservative (red) nodes mostly always connected to other conservative nodes and vice versa (same thing but with blue nodes), with very few neutral nodes connected to each other (i.e they are either connected to a liberal and/or conservative node). This means that the network tells us that conservatives and liberals do not mix well together and are separated into two groups.
